<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870804-0071 </DOCNO><HL> McDonnell GetsDefense OrdersOf $519 Million</HL><DD> 08/04/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> MD GE GLJ UTX GD GM CSCAEROSPACE (ARO)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Units of McDonnell Douglas Corp. received contracts totaling $519 million for FA-18 aircraft for the Navy and maintenance of KC-10 aircraft for the Air Force.    These funds include $514.4 million of payments in order to fix the prices of 168 FA-18 fighter-attack planes, which had been previously ordered under terms that would have allowed the contractor to adjust the prices depending on inflation and other variables.    In other awards yesterday, General Electric Co. got contracts totaling $161 million for F-404 aircraft engines for the Navy and aircraft engine research and development for the Air Force.    Units of United Technologies Corp. won contracts totaling $43.2 million for radar equipment for EA-6B aircraft, SH-60 helicopter equipment and F-404 aircraft engine production for the Navy, and aircraft engine research and development for the Air Force.    Units of General Dynamics Corp. were awarded contracts totaling $24 million for Phalanx shipboard gun system production support for the Navy and F-16 aircraft equipment for the Air Force.    Gates Learjet Corp. received a $14.5 million Air Force contract for C-21A aircraft.    Batten, Barden, Durstine andamp; Osborn received a $12.7 million Navy contract for recruitment advertising services.    General Motors Corp. won an $11.5 million Air Force contract for aircraft engine research and development.    Computer Sciences Corp. was issued a $10.4 million Army contract for teleprocessing services. </TEXT></DOC>